{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\n\nRebar is a reusable ticket, reconciliation, and review-gate system consumed through several harnesses and deployed into projects with very different stacks, repository shapes, platforms, and execution environments. Development of rebar itself happens primarily in a Python repository on macOS through current agent harnesses, which creates a risk that a technically plausible plan silently bakes rebar-project assumptions into reusable behavior.\n\nRepresentative failures include a core `rebar landing` command that encodes this repository Gerrit policy, Python-only review rules that fail to apply to a Next.js client, macOS-specific dependencies, and operations that assume the process starts inside a local project checkout. The review must catch concrete incompatibilities without requiring every plan to contain generic portability prose.\n\n## Why\n\nRebar maintainers need an early, high-recall warning when a proposed plan would break a supported client shape. Downstream clients need project-specific policy to remain in project configuration while reusable mechanisms remain usable across harnesses, target projects, platforms, execution venues, and project-location models. Dogfooding the existing project-criterion and project-coaching seams also provides a real example for client authors.\n\n## What\n\nAdd one activated project plan-review criterion, `project.portability`, through `.rebar/criteria_routing.json` and `.rebar/prompts/plan-review-project-portability.md`. It runs in Pass 1 at both container and leaf scope. It does not adjudicate validity, impact, severity, or disposition; existing Pass 2 and Pass 3 do that without modification.\n\nThe finder may emit a portability finding only when it supplies all four elements:\n\n- a citation to the explicit plan detail or mechanism carrying the assumption;\n- a materially different supported client shape;\n- the causal mechanism by which that shape fails; and\n- a specific, observable breakage scenario that Pass 2 can verify.\n\nThe compatibility counterexample matrix is:\n\n- Harness: Python library, CLI, and remote MCP clients, without assumptions specific to Claude Code, Codex, or another development harness.\n- Target project: Ruby, Python, Java, Next.js, .NET, and atypical layouts such as Terraform subprojects inside a monorepo.\n- Platform and venue: macOS, Windows, Linux, and BSD across CI, servers, and developer workstations.\n- Project location and access: in-checkout current working directory, explicitly located workspace, and server execution outside the target checkout without assuming unrestricted local filesystem access.\n\nSilence about portability is not a finding. If the reviewer cannot construct the cited, concrete counterexample, it emits no finding. Project-specific behavior is allowed when it remains project configuration rather than leaking into reusable core behavior.\n\nAdd one project-specific Pass-4 move in `.rebar/plan_review_moves.json`, applicable only when `project.portability` survives review:\n\n- id: `project-portability`\n- name: `restore rebar portability`\n- applies_when: `[\"project.portability\"]`\n- template: `Rework {subject} so it remains portable across supported rebar client shapes; keep project-specific behavior in project configuration or an explicit extension boundary.`\n\nThe existing Pass-4 applicability filter, move picker, subject validator, and deterministic renderer remain unchanged. No generic core coaching move is added.\n\n## Approach and sequencing\n\n1. Before implementation, use a fresh worktree based on current `origin/main` to run an offline experiment with temporary project overlay, prompt, and move files. Exercise the real registry, routing, ProductionBatchRunner project fan-in, move loader, applicability filter, and deterministic coaching renderer. Record the command and output on this epic. This de-risks the extension mechanism; it does not become production code.\n2. Add the rebar-project overlay, contract-bearing criterion prompt, and scoped project move as one coupled vertical slice. The criterion and move are individually incomplete: the criterion supplies the trigger and the move supplies its tailored remediation.\n3. Add focused tests with positive cases for Gerrit landing policy, Python-only criteria, macOS-only dependencies, and current-working-directory assumptions, plus negative cases proving that absent portability prose and properly project-scoped configuration do not create findings. Cover both leaf and container routing.\n4. Document the committed rebar configuration as the client-facing dogfood example and run focused plus repository-wide gates.\n\nThis approach uses the existing project extension seams instead of changing the generic four-pass kernel. It directly demonstrates the intended boundary, limits blast radius, and preserves Pass 2 and Pass 3 behavior.\n\n## Scope\n\nIn scope:\n\n- Rebar-project Pass-1 criterion configuration, prompt, and activation.\n- Rebar-project Pass-4 move configuration restricted to `project.portability`.\n- Offline wiring experiment in a fresh worktree.\n- Focused positive, negative, leaf, container, routing, and rendering tests.\n- Documentation of the project configuration as an example for clients.\n\nOut of scope:\n\n- Remediating existing portability debt discovered by the criterion.\n- Adding `rebar landing` or other rebar-project workflow policy to reusable core.\n- A generic built-in coaching move.\n- Changes to Pass 2 validity/impact adjudication or Pass 3 deterministic decisions.\n- Guaranteeing that every existing rebar feature already supports every matrix cell.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- The rebar project owns and activates `project.portability`, and the production Pass-1 routing includes it for both container and leaf plans.\n- The project move loads through the production registry, is offered only for findings carrying `project.portability`, and renders the locked project template.\n- Positive and negative fixtures demonstrate concrete counterexample discovery without a missing-prose portability tax.\n- Existing plan-review behavior remains unchanged when a client has no project overlay or project move file.\n- The experiment evidence and implementation documentation show client authors how the two project extension seams compose.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `project.portability` is activated for plan review at container and leaf scope, resolves its contract-bearing prompt, and appears in ProductionBatchRunner project fan-in. Verify: `.venv/bin/python -m pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_portability.py -k \"criterion or routing or fan_in\"`\n- [ ] Each surfaced criterion fixture contains a plan citation, alternate supported client shape, causal failure mechanism, and observable breakage scenario; plans that merely omit portability prose and plans that keep specialization in project configuration produce no finding. Verify: `.venv/bin/python -m pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_portability.py -k \"positive or negative\"`\n- [ ] The `project-portability` move loads from `.rebar/plan_review_moves.json`, is applicable only when `project.portability` is active, and deterministically renders the locked template. Verify: `.venv/bin/python -m pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_portability.py -k coaching`\n- [ ] An offline experiment from a fresh `origin/main` worktree exercises criterion activation through Pass-1 fan-in and the project move through Pass-4 applicability/rendering, with the command and successful output recorded in an epic comment. Verify: `.venv/bin/rebar show jira-reb-1003`\n- [ ] Existing overlay-absent and generic plan-review behavior remains green. Verify: `.venv/bin/python -m pytest -q tests/unit/test_criteria_overlay.py tests/unit/test_plan_review.py`\n- [ ] The project-specific configuration is documented as a client-facing example and all repository gates pass. Verify: `make lint && make typecheck && make test`\n","title":"Guard rebar plans against project-shaped portability assumptions"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784161901004170001,"uuid":"aa3482c3-f3e0-4418-994f-76ab5d497981"}